\begin_layout Standard
Consider a set of SPs whose aim is to provide different services, indexed
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1,\dots,|\mathcal{S}|$
\end_inset

, to mobile users over some geographical area.
 The geographical area under study is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 and the subarea over which service 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 has to be made available is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{\ensuremath{A}^{\sigma}}$
\end_inset

.
 Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Orange_Map"

\end_inset

 illustrates three geographical subareas over which three different services
 have to be deployed.
 For that purpose, each SP forwards its service requirements to an MNO.
 The MNO sends to the InP a Slice Resource Demand (SRD) consisting of (
\shape italic
i
\shape default
) an SRD graph accounting for the structure and SLA of the slice and (
\shape italic
ii
\shape default
) SRD coverage information related to the area 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A^{\sigma}}\subset\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 over which the service will have to be made available.
 The InP is then in charge of provisioning enough infrastructure resources
 to deploy the SFCs, whose resource demands are described by the SRD graph.
 This work focuses on the specific aspect of the SRD related to the slice
 radio coverage constraints, which impose a minimum data rate for users
 in the geographical areas where services have to be made available.
\end_layout

