\begin_layout Subsection
Infrastructure model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an infrastructure network managed by some InPs.
 We devise the special case of the cloud mobile network architecture with
 RRH nodes connected to datacenter nodes at edge and central locations as
 depicted on Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:System-architecture"

\end_inset

.
 This network is represented by a directed graph 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{\textrm{I}}=\left(\mathcal{N}_{\textrm{I}},\mathcal{E}_{\textrm{I}}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}_{\textrm{I}}$
\end_inset

 is the set of infrastructure nodes and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{\textrm{I}}$
\end_inset

 is the set of infrastructure links, which correspond to the wired connections
 between nodes of the infrastructure network.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each infrastructure node and link in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{\textrm{I}}$
\end_inset

 is characterized by a given amount of supported resources (
\shape italic
e.g
\shape default
., computing and storage for nodes as well as bandwidth for links), which
 may be allocated to network slices.
 Radio resources are exclusively provided by a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}_{\textrm{Ir}}\subset\mathcal{N}_{\textrm{I}}$
\end_inset

 of RRH nodes, whose location in some Cartesian frame attached to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{\textrm{r}}$
\end_inset

.
 The cost associated to the use of a RRH
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 consists of a fixed part 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{f}}\left(i\right)$
\end_inset

 for node disposal, and a variable part 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{r}}(i)$
\end_inset

, which depends linearly on the radio resource amount provided by that RRH.
\end_layout

