\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example of deployment of two slices in a cloud mobile network.
 Slice 1 is dedicated to a video streaming service and Slice 2 aims at providing
 video surveillance and traffic monitoring.
 The SFCs of Slice 1 consists of a virtual Video Optimizer Controller (vVOC),
 a virtual Gateway (vGW), and a virtual BBU (vBBU).
 The SFCs of Slice 2 consists of a vBBU, a vGW, a virtual Traffic Monitor
 (vTM), a vVOC, and a virtual Intrusion Detection Prevention System (vIDPS).
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:System-architecture"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
SRD Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A SRD is defined on the basis of the SLA between the SP and the MNO.
 The SLA may consider several time intervals over each of which the service
 characteristics and constraints are assumed constant, but may vary from
 one interval to the next one.
 These time intervals translate, 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default
, day and night variations of user demands.
 They last between tens of minutes and hours.
 It is of the responsibility of the SP and MNO to properly scale the requirement
s expressed in the SLA, by considering, for example, similar services deployed
 in the past.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work, one considers a given time interval specified in the SLA.
 The SLA is expressed in terms of supported service type and targeted QoS
 such as a minimum average data rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{R}_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{R}_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 for the wireless uplink (UL) and downlink (DL) traffic of each client.
 The geographical distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\sigma}(x)$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

, describes the 
\emph on
maximum
\emph default
 user/device density to be served around 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 within the considered time interval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A slice is also characterized by the amount of resources required for running
 all VNFs and links supporting all the SFCs to achieve the SLA with the
 SP.
 The SRD represents the aggregated resource requirements of these SFCs and
 its graph mimics the graph of SFCs, with SRD nodes corresponding to the
 VNFs of the SFC.
 Each SRD node is characterized by a given amount of 
\emph on
required
\emph default
 resources, 
\shape italic
e.g
\shape default
., computing and/or storage, to sustain the aggregated demand for all instances
 of a given VNF in the slice.
 Similarly, each SRD link can be characterized by the bandwidth required
 to sustain the aggregated traffic demand between the VNFs at two ends.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One assumes that the UL and DL resource demands are aggregated within a
 single node 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\text{r}}$
\end_inset

 of the SRD graph.
 The resulting aggregated UL and DL data rates 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\text{u}}\left(v_{\text{r}}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\text{d}}\left(v_{\text{r}}\right)$
\end_inset

 resulting from the coverage constraint of slice 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & r_{\textrm{u}}\left(v_{\text{r}}\right)=\underline{R}_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}\int_{\mathcal{\mathcal{A}^{\sigma}}}\rho^{\sigma}\left(x\right)\mathrm{d}x,\label{eq:SRD_UL}\\
 & r_{\textrm{d}}\left(v_{\text{r}}\right)=\underline{R}_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}\int_{\mathcal{\mathcal{A}^{\sigma}}}\rho^{\sigma}\left(x\right)\mathrm{d}x.\label{eq:SRD_DL}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Coverage-aware Resource Provisioning for Network Slices
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:ProblemFormulation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section describes a formulation of the slice resource provisioning
 problem.
 In Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Radio-Provisioning"

\end_inset

, we propose a framework to provision radio resources for multiple slices.
 The problem of joint radio and other network resource provisioning is discussed
 in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Full-resource-provisioning"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Radio Provisioning
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Radio-Provisioning"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our aim is to provision radio resources from the RRHs for the slices managed
 by an MNO with minimum deployment cost.
 For slice 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, the InP has to provide a minimum average data rate 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
(
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{R}_{\textrm{u}}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 for UL and 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{R}_{\textrm{d}}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 for DL) to each mobile user spread over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 with a density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\sigma}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For that purpose, the InP will have to provision resources from the RRH
 nodes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}$
\end_inset

.
 One assumes that every RRH node is able to provide a fixed amount 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)$
\end_inset

 of Resource Blocks (RB) per time unit to exchange data (UL and DL) with
 users.
 The amount of data transmitted using a single RB depends on the characteristics
 of the RRH, of the User Equipment (UE), and on the transmission channel
 between the RRH and the user.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the resource provisioning phase, the locations of users are unknown.
 To address this problem, an approach inspired by the subarea partitioning
 technique introduced in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{Shi2007}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is considered.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A^{\sigma}}$
\end_inset

 is partitioned into 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 convex subareas 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $=\left\{ 1,\dots,Q^{\sigma}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Instead of allocating RBs to users, RRH nodes allocate RBs to subareas.
 The way the partitioning is performed is not detailed here.
 One may consider, 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default
, a partitioning into rectangles of equal surfaces or a partitioning based
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 that provides an equal average number of users per subarea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To formulate the radio resource provisioning problem, we introduce the sets
 of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\eta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\eta}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\eta}=\left\{ \eta_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right),\eta_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)\right\} _{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}},q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma},\sigma\in\mathcal{S}}$
\end_inset

, represents the proportion of RBs provisioned by RRH
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to the users in 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 for UL and DL traffic, respectively.
 The elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\eta}$
\end_inset

 take real values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The set of binary variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\eta}}=\left\{ \widetilde{\eta}^{\sigma}\left(i\right)\right\} _{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}}$
\end_inset

 identifies whether a RRH
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathcal{N}_{\textrm{Ir}}$
\end_inset

 has provisioned some RBs to any subarea for slice 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\eta}^{\sigma}\left(i\right)=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}}\eta^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)>0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\eta}^{\sigma}\left(i\right)=0$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Single Slice 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Single_Slices"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cost related to the radio resource provisioning for slice 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 consists of a fixed part 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\textrm{f}}\left(i\right)\widetilde{\eta}^{\sigma}\left(i\right)$
\end_inset

 related to the use of a RRH and a variable part 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\textrm{r}}a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)\eta^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)$
\end_inset

 related to the amount of RBs provided by each RRH to the slice.
 A bias towards RB allocation by RRHs providing high spectral efficiency
 is obtained by the introduction of a rate-related discount 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\lambda b\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)\eta^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a positive discount factor.
 The resulting cost function 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
for the radio resources is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}c_{\textrm{rr}} & \left(\boldsymbol{\eta},\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\eta}}\right)=\sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}}c_{\textrm{f}}\left(i\right)\widetilde{\eta}^{\sigma}\left(i\right)\\
 & +\sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}}\sum_{q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}}\left[c_{\textrm{r}}-\lambda b_{\text{u}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)\right]a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)\eta_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)\\
 & +\sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}}\sum_{q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}}\left[c_{\textrm{r}}-\lambda b_{\text{d}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)\right]a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)\eta_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right).
\end{split}
\label{eq:Cover_Cost_Single}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minimization of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{rr}}\left(\boldsymbol{\eta},\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\eta}}\right)$
\end_inset

 has to be such that several constraints are satisfied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The summed proportions of RBs provided by a given RRH
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 must be less than one
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}}\left(\eta_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)+\eta_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)\right)\leqslant1,\,\forall i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}.\label{eq:Cover_EtaLessThanOne}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each subarea 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

, the total data rate provided by the allocated resource blocks should satisfy
 the minimum average user demand.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

, one should have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}}\eta_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)b_{\text{u}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)\geqslant\underline{R}_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}\int_{\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}}\rho^{\sigma}\left(x\right)\mathrm{d}x,\label{eq:Cover_MinRate_UL}\\
 & \sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}}\eta_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)b_{\text{d}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)\geqslant\underline{R}_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}\int_{\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}}\rho^{\sigma}\left(x\right)\mathrm{d}x,\label{eq:Cover_MinRate_DL}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which corresponds to the satisfaction of the geographical coverage constraints
 for UL and DL.
 Here, 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{u}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)$
\end_inset

 and
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{d}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 denote the amount of data carried by a RB for a user located in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 for UL and DL.
 Depending on the level of conservatism, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{u}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{d}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)$
\end_inset

 may represent the minimum or the average amount of data evaluated over
 the possible locations of users in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

.
 The terms 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{u}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{d}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}}\rho^{\sigma}\left(x\right)\mathrm{d}x$
\end_inset

 are fixed quantities that only depend on the RRH location 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{\textrm{r}}$
\end_inset

, on the user density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

, and on the way the partitioning of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 has been performed.
 These terms may thus be evaluated in advance, see Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Rate-Allocation-Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Summing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Cover_MinRate_DL"

\end_inset

 over all 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 and using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SRD_DL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, one gets
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \sum_{q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}}\sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}}\eta_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)b_{\text{u}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)\geqslant r_{\textrm{u}}\left(v_{\text{r}}\right),\label{eq:Cover_PerVirtualNode_UL}\\
 & \sum_{q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}}\sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}}\eta_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)b_{\text{d}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)\geqslant r_{\textrm{d}}\left(v_{\text{r}}\right),\label{eq:Cover_PerVirtualNode_DL}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which ensures, for slice 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, the satisfaction of the part of the SRD graph related to the UL and DL
 radio resource demands.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each RRH, the amount of provisioned UL and DL resources should be proportion
al to the demand expressed in the SRD graph through 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\textrm{u}}\left(v_{\text{r}}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\textrm{d}}\left(v_{\text{r}}\right)$
\end_inset

, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SRD_UL"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SRD_DL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 This avoids provisioning RRH resources taking care only of the UL or only
 of the DL traffic.
 This has to be ensured for all subareas 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\eta_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)b_{\text{u}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)}{r_{\textrm{u}}\left(v_{\text{r}}\right)}=\frac{\eta_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)b_{\text{d}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)}{r_{\textrm{d}}\left(v_{\text{r}}\right)}.\label{eq:Proportionality}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nonlinear relation between 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\eta^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)=\eta_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)+\eta_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\eta}^{\sigma}\left(i\right)$
\end_inset

 can be linearly expressed as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0\leq\widetilde{\eta}^{\sigma}\left(i\right)-\sum_{q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}}\eta^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)<1,\,\forall i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}},\forall\sigma\in\mathcal{S}.\label{eq:Cover_RelationEta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the radio provisioning problem consists in finding 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\widehat{\boldsymbol{\eta}},\widehat{\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\eta}}})=\argminA_{\boldsymbol{\eta},\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\eta}}}c_{\text{rr}}\left(\boldsymbol{\eta},\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\eta}}\right),\,\text{subject to: \,}\eqref{eq:Cover_EtaLessThanOne}-\eqref{eq:Cover_RelationEta},
\]

\end_inset

which is an MILP problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Multiple Slices
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Multiple_Slices"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When several SRD graphs for slices indexed 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 have to be considered, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Cover_Cost_Single"

\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}c_{\textrm{rr}} & \left(\boldsymbol{\eta},\widetilde{\boldsymbol{\eta}}\right)=\sum_{\sigma\in\mathcal{S}}\sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}}c_{\textrm{f}}\left(i\right)\widetilde{\eta}^{\sigma}\left(i\right)\\
 & +\sum_{\sigma\in\mathcal{S}}\sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}}\sum_{q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}}\left[c_{\textrm{r}}-\lambda b_{\text{u}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)\right]a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)\eta_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)\\
 & +\sum_{\sigma\in\mathcal{S}}\sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}}\sum_{q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}}\left[c_{\textrm{r}}-\lambda b_{\text{d}}\left(x_{i}^{\textrm{r}},\mathcal{A}_{q}^{\sigma}\right)\right]a_{\text{r}}\left(i\right)\eta_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right),
\end{split}
\label{eq:Cover_Cost_Multi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the constraints 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Cover_MinRate_UL"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Cover_RelationEta"

\end_inset

 and the constraint 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Cover_EtaLessThanOne"

\end_inset

 replaced by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{\sigma\in\mathcal{S}}\sum_{q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\sigma}}\left(\eta_{\text{u}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)+\eta_{\text{d}}^{\sigma}\left(i,q\right)\right)\leqslant1,\,\forall i\in\mathcal{N}_{\text{Ir}}.\label{eq:Cover_Multi_EtaLessThanOne}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Full resource provisioning for slices
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Full-resource-provisioning"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To complete the slice resource provisioning, one has to account for other
 resources in terms of computing, storage, and networking requirements to
 run the interconnected VNFs that are parts of the slice.
 A joint provisioning of radio and other network resources should be considered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This provisioning is represented by a mapping between the infrastructure
 graph 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{\textrm{I}}$
\end_inset

 and the SRD graph, as depicted in Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SRDProvExample"

\end_inset

.
 In this example, the slice 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is described by an SRD graph aggregating the demands of several linear
 SFCs.
\end_layout

