\begin_layout Standard
An additional set of constraints for these other resources needs to be introduce
d.
 This set of constraints, which expresses the other resource demands for
 each 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, has to be consistent with the coverage constraints presented in Sections
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Single_Slices"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Multiple_Slices"

\end_inset

.
 For instance, the other types of network resources (
\shape italic
e.g
\shape default
., link bandwidth or node storage capacity) provisioned by an infrastructure
 node should be commensurate with the provisioned radio resources.
 When considering demands on both UL and DL traffic, it is relevant to ensure
 the balance between radio and other network resources provisioned by infrastruc
ture nodes and links.
 Details of those constraints can be found in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{Luu2019}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, where a two-step algorithm to solve the joint radio and other network
 resources provisioning problem is introduced.
 The radio provisioning proposed in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Multiple_Slices"

\end_inset

 is first achieved.
 Then, only the subset of infrastructure nodes that contains RRHs involved
 in the slice coverage and identified from the first step are considered
 in the resource provisioning for the remaining functions and links of the
 slice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Evaluation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Evaluation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, one compares via simulations the performance of three different
 radio resource provisioning schemes for network slicing: a Sequential approach
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{SR}$
\end_inset

), a Joint approach (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{JR}$
\end_inset

) and a Baseline approach.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{SR}$
\end_inset

, resources are provisioned slice by slice by solving the single slice MILP
 problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Cover_Cost_Single"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Cover_RelationEta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{JR}$
\end_inset

, provisioning is performed taking into account all slices simultaneously
 and solving the multiple slices MILP problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Cover_Cost_Multi"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Cover_Multi_EtaLessThanOne"

\end_inset

.
 All simulations are performed with the CPLEX MILP solver interfaced with
 MATLAB.
 The Baseline approach works slice-by-slice, as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{SR}$
\end_inset

 approach.
 For each slice, the RRHs provisioning resources to users located in subarea
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 are selected starting from those providing the highest Signal-to-Noise
 (SNR) ratio, whatever the cost for using those RRHs, contrary to what is
 done by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{JR}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{SR}$
\end_inset

 approaches.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Heterogeneous cellular networks will be considered.
 Due to the large difference between the transmit power of macrocells and
 of smaller cells with lower power, 
\shape italic
e.g
\shape default
