\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{JR}$
\end_inset

 approach outperforms the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{SR}$
\end_inset

 and Baseline approaches in terms of radio cost and utilization of RRH nodes:
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{JR}$
\end_inset

 approach aims at finding the optimal solution for the whole problem, 
\shape italic
i.e
\shape default
., provisioning for all the slices, while the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{SR}$
\end_inset

 and Baseline approaches only account for the constraints of each slice
 sequentially.
 The difference in performance of these three methods increases when four
 slices and more are simultaneously considered.
 For instance, with six slices, a cost reduction of 
\begin_inset Formula $2.9\%$
\end_inset

 compared to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{SR}$
\end_inset

 approach and 
\begin_inset Formula $96\%$
\end_inset

 compared to the baseline approach is observed in favor of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{JR}$
\end_inset

 approach, see Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:k_PerBlock"

\end_inset

.
 With eight slices, the provisioning cost reductions are 
\begin_inset Formula $3.3\%$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $105\%$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
